 ways of interpreting human experience can challenge our assumptions about emotions and enrich our lives.Brings to light a rich lexicon of emotion from ancient IndiaUses the Indian genre of a “treasury,” or wordbook, to explore the contours of classical Indian thought in three of the subcontinent’s earliest languages—Sanskrit, Pali, and PrakritFeatures 177 alphabetical entries, from abhaya (“fearlessness”) to yoga (“the discipline of calm”)Draws on a wealth of literary, religious, and philosophical writings from classical IndiaIncludes synonyms, antonyms, related words, and suggestions for further readingInvites readers to engage in the cross-cultural study of emotionsReveals the many different ways of naming and interpreting human experience  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aBuddhismxPsychology. 0aEmotionsvTerminology. 0aEmotionsxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aEmotionsxSocial aspectszIndiaxHistory. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / Indic.2bisacsh  aAbhilasha.  aAccreditation.  aAddition.  aAnecdote.  aArhat.  aAwareness.  aBangle.  aBauble.  aBhakti.  aBhavabhuti.  aBhikkhu.  aBhima.  aBuddhism.  aCivics.  aConfabulation.  aConsciousness.  aConsideration.  aContrasting and categorization of emotions.  aCouplet.  aDeclaration of love.  aDeference.  aDeliberation.  aDialectic.  aDisposition.  aDukkha.  aEdict.  aEmbellishment.  aEmotion.  aEmotionality.  aEmpathy.  aEntitlement.  aEpic poetry.  aEpistemic community.  aExplanation.  aFeeling.  aFrisson.  aGoad.  aGod.  aHandbook.  aHeart (symbol).  aHinglish.  aIdeology.  aIngredient.  aKaurava.  aKrodha (Mental factor).  aKshanti.  aKunti.  aMetta.  aMotivated reasoning.  aMudita.  aNarrative.  aNeologism.  aOf Education.  aParable.  aPersonal identit